The core idea is to provide a unique scattering association to different shielding portions of the broadband THz field illumination (as per ref46,47) with a knife-edge moving in the near-field of the scatterer. The scatterer waveform obtained by the 2D time-domain detection set is used as a base to reconstruct a 1D transmission matrix. Once the transmission matrix is known, the image of any 1D object can be deterministically retrieved. Figure 2a illustrates a typical setting for a knife-edge (a thin conductive blade clipping a Gaussian beam) scan, where the THz near-field imager collects scattered fields from the sample partially illuminated. We can write the spatiotemporal field profile (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
